compound of Old Welsh <i>creic</i> ‘rock’ + Older Scots <i>tun</i> ‘farm, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). In Ireland and Britain, this form of the name is now found chiefly in northern Ireland; the more usual Scottish forms are   Crichton   and   Crighton  .","Irish: sometimes used for Gaelic <b>Ó Creacháin</b> or <b>Ó Criocháin</b> (see   Crehan  ).","English: habitational name from Creighton in Staffordshire, named with Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Crichton was born about 1230, his father, William Crichton, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Crichton, was 32. He married Edna de Crichton in 1258, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1300, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 72."},"et":{"Abt 1230–Abt 1300":"umbes 1230–umbes 1300","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1265–1340":"1265–1340","1270–1317":"1270–1317","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1258":"1258","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1317":"1317","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Pathead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Midl